<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-302-020  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 302 020.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>P.C. Letter  March 20 1990 v6 n4 p7(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT PCW Communications Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Font wars expand into new theaters: desktop publishing.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alsop, Stewart.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   PostScript (Printer software) (usage).andO;Topic:     SAADesktop PublishingFonts.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>FONT WARS EXPAND INTO NEW THEATERSandM;Most commentators have focused on IBM's announcement of SAA-level support forAdobe's Postscript font format as the most significant recent announcement inthe font wars.andP;  I have a feeling thought that Hewlett Packard's announcementof the Laserjett III printer with built-in font-scaling will actually havemore of an impact in the real world.andM;Adobe's ability to gain support from IBM for its font format is realtestament to the company's technical vision.andP;  What IBM really likes aboutAdobe's fonts is that they are generic enough that they can be used acrossIBM's entire computing product line -- mainframes, minicomputers, andpersonal computers (at least ones equipped with OS/2).andP;  And that's thefundamental vision of cross-platform font formats that Adobe has beenpromoting for the past six months.andP;  But the fact is that there are already atremendous number of fonts in the field in the Adobe format already and thatisn't going to change.andM;What will change is the fact that Hewlett Packard will likely sell hundredsof thousands of Laserjet III printers in the next year or two that will havethe built in capability to scale font outlines in the Intellifont formatdeveloped by Agfa Compugraphic.andP;  And that will mean that there will be yetanother separate and distinct set of fonts that need to be catalogued andmanaged in PCs around the world.andP;  So we don't just face a world of Adobe andthe newly named Truetype fonts from Apple and Microsoft: the likelihood isthat a lot of offices will end up with three different sets of fonts:Truetype, Postscript, and Intellifont.andO;</TEXT></DOC>